<subSubSection pageId="91" pageNumber="92" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="91.[151,1436,150,429]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,222,248]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Remarks</emphasis>
. So far as is known, this species is endemic to 
<collectingRegion box="[840,1018,222,248]" country="Russia" name="Primorskiy" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Primorskij Kraj</collectingRegion>
. In our molecular analysis, the maximum intraspecific 
<emphasis box="[361,375,259,284]" italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">p</emphasis>
-distance was 0.2% in COI (n=3) and 0% in NaK (n=3). The nearest neighbour was 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Takeuchi" authorityYear="1930" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kamikochensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">P. kamikochensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(a member of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Kirby" authorityYear="1882" box="[443,588,294,320]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albopictus">
<emphasis box="[443,588,294,320]" italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">P. albopictus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgroup), diverging by a minimum of 3.1% in the COI analysis, and by a minimum of 0.8% in the NaK analysis. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shinohara &amp; Taeger" authorityYear="2007" box="[598,789,330,356]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leleji">
<emphasis box="[598,789,330,356]" italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Pamphilius leleji</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was recovered as sister to the clade 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Kirby" authorityYear="1882" box="[1198,1343,330,356]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albopictus">
<emphasis box="[1198,1343,330,356]" italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">P. albopictus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Takeuchi" authorityYear="1930" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kamikochensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">P. kamikochensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 100% UFBoot support in the COI tree (
<figureCitation box="[793,888,366,392]" captionStart="FIGURE 148" captionStartId="235.[151,250,1827,1851]" captionTargetBox="[157,1427,198,1794]" captionTargetId="figure-19@235.[151,1436,181,1803]" captionTargetPageId="235" captionText="FIGURE 148. Condensed ML tree based on CO1 gene sequences, with details of Pamphilius vafer group, part 1." pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Fig. 148</figureCitation>
) but as sister to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="V. Vikberg" authorityYear="1971" box="[1070,1225,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aucupariae">
<emphasis box="[1070,1225,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">P. aucupariae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 98% UFBoot support in the NaK tree (
<figureCitation box="[429,527,402,428]" captionStart="FIGURE 161" captionStartId="246.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[177,1403,189,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-26@246.[171,1417,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="246" captionText="FIGURE 161. Condensed ML tree based on NaK gene sequences, with details of Pamphilius vafer group, part 2." pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Fig. 161</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
